direction: down
vars: {
  d2-config: {
    layout-engine: elk
    theme-id: 4
  }
}
title: |md
  # Enqueue: Two-Step CAS Protocol
  **Michael-Scott Queue (M3)**
| {near: top-center}
row1: "" {
  direction: right
  style.stroke: transparent
  style.fill: transparent
  phase1: {
    direction: down
    label: "PHASE 1: Link New Node"
    width: 320
    step1: {
      label: "Step 1: Read tail & tail->next"
      width: 280
      code: |'c
        tail = atomic_load(&queue->tail);
        next = atomic_load(&tail->next);
        // next == NULL (ready to link)
      '|
    }
    step2: {
      label: "Step 2: CAS tail->next"
      width: 280
      code: |'c
        CAS(&tail->next, NULL, new_node)
        // Atomic link at tail
      '|
    }
    p1_result: {
      label: "Result: Node Linked"
      width: 280
      state: |md
        **Linearization Point**
        `tail->next` now points to `new_node`
        Element is **logically in queue**
      |
    }
    step1 -> step2: "next == NULL"
    step2 -> p1_result: "CAS success"
  }
  phase2: {
    direction: down
    label: "PHASE 2: Swing Tail"
    width: 320
    step3: {
      label: "Step 3: Advance tail"
      width: 280
      code: |'c
        CAS(&queue->tail, tail, new_node)
        // Swing tail pointer
      '|
    }
    p2_result: {
      label: "Result: Tail Advanced"
      width: 280
      state: |md
        **Tail now points to new_node**
        Queue state is fully consistent
        Other threads see correct tail
      |
    }
    step3 -> p2_result: "CAS success"
  }
  arrow: {
    shape: text
    label: "→"
    style.font-size: 40
    style.fill: transparent
    style.stroke: transparent
  }
  phase1 -> arrow
  arrow -> phase2
}
row2: "" {
  direction: right
  style.stroke: transparent
  style.fill: transparent
  lagging: {
    direction: down
    label: "LAGGING TAIL: Thread Stalls Between Phases"
    width: 680
    before: {
      label: "Before: Thread A stalls after Phase 1"
      width: 300
      struct1: {
        shape: sql_table
        label: "Queue State"
        f1: "head | ptr | → sentinel"
        f2: "tail | ptr | → node_B (stale!)"
        f3: "sentinel.next | ptr | → node_A"
        f4: "node_A.next | ptr | → NULL"
        note: "Thread A linked node_A but\ndidn't swing tail yet"
      }
    }
    arrow2: {
      shape: text
      label: "→"
      style.font-size: 40
      style.fill: transparent
      style.stroke: transparent
    }
    after: {
      label: "Helping: Thread B advances tail"
      width: 300
      struct2: {
        shape: sql_table
        label: "Thread B observes tail->next != NULL"
        f1: "Condition | bool | tail->next != NULL"
        f2: "Action | CAS | tail → tail->next"
        f3: "Result | ptr | tail → node_A"
        note: "Thread B helps complete\nThread A's enqueue!"
      }
    }
    before -> arrow2
    arrow2 -> after
  }
}
row3: "" {
  direction: right
  style.stroke: transparent
  style.fill: transparent
  helping: {
    direction: down
    label: "HELPING MECHANISM: Code Path"
    width: 680
    code_block: {
      label: "Enqueue with Helping (ms_queue.c)"
      width: 640
      code: |'c
        void ms_enqueue(MSQueue* queue, int64_t value) {
            Node* new_node = malloc(sizeof(Node));
            new_node->value = value;
            new_node->next = NULL;
            while (true) {
                tail = atomic_load(&queue->tail);
                next = atomic_load(&tail->next);
                if (tail == atomic_load(&queue->tail)) {  // Consistency check
                    if (next == NULL) {
                        // PHASE 1: Link new node
                        if (CAS(&tail->next, NULL, new_node)) {
                            // PHASE 2: Swing tail (can fail - others may help)
                            CAS(&queue->tail, tail, new_node);
                            return;
                        }
                    } else {
                        // HELPING: Tail is lagging!
                        // Another thread linked but didn't swing tail
                        CAS(&queue->tail, tail, next);  // Advance it ourselves
                    }
                }
            }
        }
      '|
    }
  }
}
legend: {
  near: bottom-center
  label: "Key Insight"
  insight: |md
    **Why two phases?** We can only CAS one memory location at a time.
    - Phase 1 modifies `tail->next` (the node's next field)
    - Phase 2 modifies `queue->tail` (the queue's tail pointer)
    **Helping ensures lock-freedom**: If Thread A stalls, Thread B can observe the
    intermediate state (`tail->next != NULL`) and complete the tail swing.
    No thread can block progress indefinitely.
  |
}
row1 -> row2: "If thread descheduled"
row2 -> row3: "Helping protocol"